  "prompt": "What are the major aspects covered under ISO/TS 16949 Audit?",
  "response": "ISO/TS 16949, which has been replaced by IATF 16949:2016, was a technical specification for automotive quality management systems. It was developed by the International Automotive Task Force (IATF) and was aligned with ISO 9001. The audit process under ISO/TS 16949 covered several major aspects to ensure compliance with the standard and the effectiveness of the quality management system (QMS) in the automotive industry. Here are the key aspects typically covered during an ISO/TS 16949 audit:\n\n1. **Context of the Organization**:\n   - Understanding the organization and its context.\n   - Understanding the needs and expectations of interested parties.\n   - Determining the scope of the QMS.\n\n2. **Leadership**:\n   - Leadership and commitment.\n   - Quality policy.\n   - Organizational roles, responsibilities, and authorities.\n\n3. **Planning**:\n   - Actions to address risks and opportunities.\n   - Quality objectives and planning to achieve them.\n   - Planning of changes.\n\n4. **Support**:\n   - Resources (human resources, infrastructure, environment for the operation of processes).\n   - Competencies, awareness, and training.\n   - Communication.\n   - Documented information (control of documents and records).\n\n5. **Operation**:\n   - Operational planning and control.\n   - Requirements for products and services.\n   - Design and development of products and services.\n   - Control of externally provided processes, products, and services.\n   - Production processes (control of production and service provision).\n   - Identification and traceability.\n   - Property belonging to customers or external providers.\n   - Preservation of products.\n   - Post-delivery activities.\n   - Control of changes.\n   - Release of products and services.\n   - Control of nonconforming outputs.\n\n6. **Performance Evaluation**:\n   - Monitoring, measurement, analysis, and evaluation.\n   - Internal audits.\n   - Management review.\n\n7. **Improvement**:\n   - General requirements.\n   - Nonconformity and corrective action.\n   - Continual improvement.\n\nAdditionally, ISO/TS 16949 included specific automotive industry requirements, which were also audited. These included: \n   - Process approach and risk management.\n   - Customer-specific requirements (CSRs).\n   - Product safety.\n   - Responsibility for conformity to product and process requirements.\n   - Internal laboratory requirements.\n   - External laboratory requirements.\n   - Control of externally provided products, processes, and services.\n   - Responsibility for design and development.\n   - Control of changes.\n   - Core tools of the automotive industry (APQP - Advanced Product Quality Planning, FMEA - Failure Mode and Effects Analysis, MSA - Measurement Systems Analysis, SPC - Statistical Process Control, and PPAP - Production Part Approval Process).\n\nIt is important to note that since ISO/TS 16949 is no longer in effect, organizations in the automotive sector should now refer to IATF 16949:2016 for their quality management system compliance and certification audits.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
